BMEB W4020 Project #2 Handout¶

The goal of this project is to implement a decoding algorithm for the olfactory processing pathway of Drosophila Malenogaster (fruitfly). Specifically, you are asked to implement a simple model of an olfactory channel in fruit flies as shown below:

I/O Relationship¶

Input $u(t)$¶

An odor with a concentration profile $u=u(t)$, $t \in [0, 500]$(in ms) is sensed by some 40 to 50 olfactory sensory neurons (OSNs).

Assume that the stimulus concentration at the input of the OSNs is modeled as a bandlimited function of the form $$ u(t)= \sum_{k=1}^{15} u(kT) \frac{\sin \Omega (t-kT)}{\Omega (t-kT)}, $$ where $\Omega = 2 \pi \cdot 25$ Hz and $T=\frac{\pi}{\Omega}$.

1st Layer: Olfactory Sensory Neurons (OSNs): $u(t) \rightarrow (t_k^{m}), m = 1,\ldots M$¶

The input $u(t)$ is first processed by the OSNs in a SIMO fashion (a scaled up version of the HW4-P2). Each parallel processing pathway is modeled as a [Filter]-[PIF] circuit.

  1. The temporal receptive fields of the OSNs are of the form $$ h^i (t) = h_{max}^i \exp(-\frac{t}{\tau^i}) $$ for $t \geq 0$ and zero otherwise.
  2. All neurons are modeled as IAF neurons. See Project Details for information about the requirement of the IAF neurons.

2nd Layer: Glomeruli: $\{(t_k^{m})\}_{m} \rightarrow \{v^{1n}\}_{n}, m = 1,\ldots M, n = 1,\ldots N$¶

The output spike $(t_{k}^{m})$ trains from the OSNs ($1,\ldots, M$) are processed in a region called the Glomeruli in the Antennal Lobe. Glomerular synapses are modeled as $\alpha$-functions of the form $$ h^{ij}(t)= h_{max}^{ij} \frac{t}{\tau^{ij}}\exp(1- 50\frac{t}{\tau^{ij}}) $$

3rd Layer: Projection Neurons (PNs): $v^{1n} \rightarrow (t_k^{1n}), n = 1,\ldots N$¶

The output of the glomeruli are mapped into distinctive projection neurons, 10-20 PNs.

  1. All neurons are modeled as IAF neurons. See Project Details for information about the requirement of the IAF neurons.

Project Details:¶

  1. Realize the circuit shown in figure above. Choose the parameters of the IAF neurons such that the average number of spikes for OSNs is below 50 and PNs is below 100 spikes/s. Specify the average spike rate of every neuron in the circuit above. Assume that $\tau^i$ is uniformly distributed in the time interval $[15, 25]$ (ms) and that $\tau^{ij}$ is uniformly distributed on the time interval $[350, 450]$ (ms) for all $i = 1,2, ... , N,$ and $j=1,2,...,M$. Further assume that $h^{i}_{max},h^{ij}_{max}$ is uniformly distributed in the range $[1,5]$.
    • Produce the following plots (can be in a subplot):
      1. Input $u(t)$, pick one of the filters $h^{i}(t)$ and filtered input $v^{i}$
      2. OSN spiking, using the utils.plotRaster function
      3. OSN spike rates, also draw a line indicating 50 Hz
      4. Glomeruli filter $h^{nm}$, output $v^{1n}$, plot a number of filters and outputs that you consider appropriate
      5. PN spiking, using the utils.plotRaster function
      6. PN spike rates, also draw a line indicating 100 Hz
  2. Recover the odor stimulus $u$ from the OSN output spike sequence $(t_k^i), i=1,2,\ldots,M$.
    • Produce the following plots (can be in a subplot):
      1. recovered $\tilde{u}$ vs $u$
      2. error of the recovery (plot absolute error in dB scale)
  3. Recover the Glomeruli outputs $v^{1,n},n=1,\ldots,N$ from the PN output spike sequence $(t_k^1n), n=1,2,\ldots,N$.
    • Produce the following plots (can be in a subplot):
      1. recovered $\tilde{v^{1n}}$ vs $v^{1n}$. plot a few example recovery outputs.
      2. error of the recovery (plot absolute error in dB scale)
  4. We attempt end-to-end recovery by reducing the OSN+Glomeruli layers into parallel filters. Assume that the OSN+Glomeruli processing is a linear process, evaluate the transfer function $\tilde{h}^{1n}$ between $v^{1n}, n=1,2,\ldots,N,$ and $u$, i.e., evaluate the ratio between the Fourier transform of the aggregate dendritic current $v^{1n}, n=1,2,\ldots,N,$ and the Fourier transform of the odor concentration profile $u$, and then taking the inverse fourier transform of that.
    • Produce the following plots (can be in a subplot):
      1. Magnitude spectrum of glomeruli output $|\mathcal{F} v^{1n}|$
      2. Magnitude spectrum of OSN input $|\mathcal{F} u|$,
      3. Magnitude spectrum of identified filter $|\mathcal{F} \tilde{h}^{1n}|$
  5. Recover the odor stimulus from the PN spike sequence $(t_k^{1j}), j=1,2,...,N$ assume a SIMO [Filter]-[LIF] configuration where the [Filter] is the filters representing OSN+Glomeruli layers identified from the step above.
    • Produce the following plots (can be in a subplot):
      1. recovered $\tilde{u}$ vs $u$
      2. error of the recovery (plot absolute error in dB scale, you should see error <=40dB)
  6. How well did the end-to-end recovery (PN output to OSN input) perform? It is not likely to perform well. If it does not perform well for you, can you answer why?

% Using material from lecture 9, not to be released
clearvars; close all; clc;
rng(20184020);
% Generate Signal in Sinc kernel
signal_generator = @(t, sample, sample_time,omega) ...
                    sum( diag(sample) * sinc( (repmat(t, size(sample_time))- ...
                    repmat(sample_time, size(t)))/pi*omega)/pi*omega);

In [3]:



    


%% Constants
M = 50; % sensory neurons
N = 20;  % projection neurons



    















    
























In [4]:



    


%% Filterbank definitions
h_OSN = @(t, hmax_OSN, tau_OSN) max(hmax_OSN*exp(-t/tau_OSN), 0).*(t>=0);
h_PN = @(t, hmax_PN, tau_PN) max(hmax_PN*(t/tau_PN).* exp(1-50*t/tau_PN), 0).*(t>=0);



    















    
























In [5]:



    


% Initialize bandlimited stimulus

dt     = 1e-5;                                      % set time step
t      = 0:dt:0.5;                                 % set simulation time
omega  = 2*pi*25;                                   % set cutoff frequency
T      = pi/omega;                                  % set sampling period
st     = (floor(t(1)/T)+1:floor(t(end)/T)+1)*T;     % set sample times
s      = rand(numel(st), 1);                    % set samples of the stimulus
u      = signal_generator(t, s, st', omega);        % generate the stimulus
u      = u/max(abs(u));                             % normalize the stimulus

% OSN encoding
delta_l1 = 0.012*ones(M,1);
kappa_l1 = ones(M,1);
b_l1 = ones(M,1);

h_l1 = zeros(M,numel(t));

for i=1:M
    h_l1(i,:) = h_OSN(t,1+4*rand(1),(15+10*rand(1))*1e-3);
end

tk_OSN = OSN(t,u,h_l1,b_l1,kappa_l1,delta_l1);
spkavg_l1 = sum(cellfun(@numel,tk_OSN))/M;

spike_l1 = zeros(M,length(t));
for i=1:M
    spike_l1(i,round(tk_OSN{i}/dt+1))=1;
end

%% 2. OSN Decoding & Recovery
dim = 0;
for i=1:M
   dim = dim+length(tk_OSN{i})-1;
end

temp = zeros(1,M+1);
for i=2:M+1         %Find out the cumulative lengths of tk
    temp(i)=temp(i-1)+length(tk_OSN{i-1})-1;
end

q_l1 = zeros(dim,1);
G_l1 = zeros(dim);

for i=1:M
    q_l1(temp(i)+1:temp(i)+length(tk_OSN{i})-1) = kappa_l1(i)*delta_l1(i) - b_l1(i)*diff(tk_OSN{i})';
end



    















    
























In [16]:



    


% Finding G
t_long = -0.5:dt:0.5;

for j=1:M
    cum_hg = dt*cumtrapz(dt*conv(h_l1(j,:),sinc(t_long/T)/T));
    sk = (tk_OSN{j}(1:end-1)+tk_OSN{j}(2:end))/2;
    for i =1:M
        for k = 1:length(tk_OSN{j})-1
            G_l1(temp(i)+1:temp(i)+length(tk_OSN{i})-1,temp(j)+k) = diff(cum_hg(round((tk_OSN{i} -sk(k) - t_long(1))/dt)+1));
        end
    end
end



    















    
























In [17]:



    


% Reconstruction
u_rec = zeros(size(t));

c = pinv(G_l1,1e-3)*q_l1;
for j=1:M
    sk = (tk_OSN{j}(1:end-1)+tk_OSN{j}(2:end))/2;
    u_rec = u_rec + signal_generator(t,c(temp(j)+1:temp(j+1)),sk',omega);
end

% 3. PN Decoding & Recovery
v_PN_rec = zeros(N,numel(t));
omega_new = 2*pi*100;
T_new = pi/omega_new;

for i=1:N
    q_l2 = kappa_l2(i)*delta_l2(i) - b_l2(i)*diff(tk_PN{i}');
    sk = (tk_PN{i}(2:end) + tk_PN{i}(1:end-1))/2;
    G_l2 = zeros(numel(tk_PN{i})-1);
    for j = 1:numel(sk)
        temp = dt*cumtrapz( sinc((t-sk(j))/T_new)/T_new );
        G_l2(:,j) = diff( temp( round( (tk_PN{i}-t(1))/dt )+1 ) );
    end
    
    c = pinv(G_l2,1e-6)*q_l2;

    v_PN_rec(i,:) = signal_generator(t,c,sk',omega_new);
end

% 5. End-to-End Recovery
dim = 0;
for i=1:N
   dim = dim+length(tk_PN{i})-1;
end

temp = zeros(1,N+1);
for i=2:N+1         %Find out the cumulative lengths of tk
    temp(i)=temp(i-1)+length(tk_PN{i-1})-1;
end

q = zeros(dim,1);
G = zeros(dim);

for i=1:N
    q(temp(i)+1:temp(i)+length(tk_PN{i})-1) = kappa_l2(i)*delta_l2(i) - b_l2(i)*diff(tk_PN{i})';
end

t_long = -0.5:dt:0.5;

for j=1:N
    cum_hg = dt*cumtrapz(dt*conv(h_rec(j,:),sinc(t_long/T)/T));
    sk = (tk_PN{j}(1:end-1)+tk_PN{j}(2:end))/2;
    for i =1:N
        for k = 1:length(tk_OSN{j})-1
            G(temp(i)+1:temp(i)+length(tk_PN{i})-1,temp(j)+k) = diff(cum_hg(round((tk_PN{i} -sk(k) - t_long(1))/dt)+1));
        end
    end
end

As is evident from the above plot, the end-to-end recovery did not perform very well. In fact, the recovered stimulus is not even in the same range as the input stimulus. The main reason for this is that due to the structure of the glomerulus and the and mixing of spiking activity of different OSNs, the parallelization approximation is invalid, and the hypothetical filters $\tilde{h}_{1n}$ do not model the OSN + Glomerulus well. This problem also stems from the fact that we are replacing a highly non-linear OSN spiking followed by glomerulus with a linear filter bank. Thus, while we can recover u from tk_OSN using $h_m$, we can't recover u from tk_PN using the hypothetical parallelized filters.


In the code, this problem manifests in the form that the coefficients of G are too small, and to be able to invert it without having the resulting values blow up, we have to set high tolerance values (~1e-2,1e-3), and therefore, the c matrix is highly inaccurate. Consequently, the high $c_k$ values lead to high scaling of basis sinc functions, and ultimately the range of the reconstructed signal blows up.
